{{Infobox magazine | title = Bābā Šamal | logo = | logo_size = 180px | image_file = Baba Shamal Ausgabe 13.jpg | image_size = 180px | image_alt = | image_caption = | editor = Reżā Ganjaʾī | editor_title = | previous_editor = | staff_writer = | photographer = | category = Satire | frequency = Weekly (until 1945) | format = | circulation = | publisher = | paid_circulation = | unpaid_circulation = | circulation_year = | total_circulation = | founder = | founded = 1943 | firstdate = | finaldate = 1947 | finalnumber = | company = | country = Iran | based = | language = Persian | website = [http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:5:1-108131 Bābā Šamal] | issn = | oclc = }}
The Persian journal '''''Baba Shamal''''' was one of the most famous political satire magazines in [[Iran]].<ref>The Encyclopaedia Iranica, http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ganjai-</ref> It was published weekly between 1943 and 1945 by Reżā Ganjaʾī (1918–1995). After his return from Europe in 1947, 50 volumes more were distributed.<ref>Lawrence Elwell-Sutton, “Iranian Press 1941-47,” Iran 6, 1968, p. 80.</ref><ref>The Encyclopaedia Iranica, http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/baba-samal</ref> Ganjaʾī was a cabinet member and a university professor for engineering. Before and after his publishership Ganjaʾī held some important positions in ministries and in the banking and insurance sector.<ref>The Encyclopaedia Iranica, http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ganjai-</ref> He published his articles under the [[pseudonym]] “Donb-al-mohandesīn“.<ref>The Encyclopaedia Iranica, http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ganjai-</ref> Many well-known Iranian satirists, poets and authors belong to his supporters and co-workers, i.a. Rahī Moʿayyerī („Zāḡča“), Eqteṣād („Shaikh Pašm-al-Dīn“), Fozūnī („Mohandes-al-Šoʿarāʾ“) and Ṣahbā („Shaikh Somā“). The journal was widespread in Iran and was characterized by its everyday language and colloquial style. The general [[satirical]] opinion of the authors found its expression in current daily politics which was supplemented by partly colored caricatures and drawings. In general the journal's position was nationalistic, independent and moderate. However, its critique led – under the pressure of censorship – to its suspension in 1947.<ref>Lawrence Elwell-Sutton, “Iranian Press 1941-47,” Iran 6, 1968, p. 80.</ref>
