The '''2008 Istanbul Fireworks Explosion''' occurred on 1 February 2008. An unlicensed [[fireworks]] factory exploded accidentally, leaving by some reports at least 22 people dead and at least 100 injured;<ref name = nytimes >{{cite news | title = Fireworks Explosion in Istanbul Kills 22 | date = 2008-02-01 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/01/world/europe/01turkey.html?hp | work = THE NEW YORK TIMES | accessdate = 2011-09-04}}</ref> others sources reported the death toll was 17 and 40 injured.<ref name = skynews >{{cite news | title = Illegal Fireworks Blast Leaves 17 Dead | date = 2008-01-31 | url = http://news.sky.com/home/world-news/article/1303378 | work = SKY News | accessdate = 2011-09-04}}</ref> The building that housed the unlicensed factory was in [[Davutpaşa]], an industrial neighborhood. It was a multistory workshop complex it shared with other manufacturers of paint, socks and textiles. Two separate explosions<ref name=todayszaman>{{cite news | title = Could factory blast have been averted? | date = 2008-02-02 | publisher = TODAY'S ZAMAN | url = http://www.todayszaman.com/news-133110-could-factory-blast-have-been-averted.html | work = todayszaman.com | accessdate = 2011-09-04 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121018121345/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-133110-could-factory-blast-have-been-averted.html | archivedate = 2012-10-18 | df =  }}</ref> were reported some five minutes apart from each other, the first possibly happening in the top floor fireworks factory, and the second larger explosion, reportedly emanating from the basement boilers where the paint manufacturing was located.<ref name = skynews />

After the incident the building was partially collapsed and this had caused many of the victims to be crushed to death when floors collapsed.<ref name = nytimes />

The factory had reportedly been shut down by authorities twice prior to this incident, but continued to operate illegally.<ref name = todayszaman />

